<li style="margin-left:20px">Not about me personally, but something that affects the field in general: after Elsevier refused to transfer <i>Lingua</i> to an open-access model, all editors resigned. The same editorial team has created a new, fully open-access, journal, <a href="http://www.glossa-journal.org" target="_blank"><i>Glossa</i></a>, which is <i>Lingua</i>'s rightful continuation despite Elsevier's attempts to own the name and all the work that is behind it. Here is a <a href="http://kaivonfintel.org/2015/11/05/lingua-roundup/" target="_blank">summary</a> on Kai von Fintel's blog and also a <a href="http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=22162" target="_blank">post</a> at Language Log. This is part of a broader movement of making science accessible to public: mathematicians, for example, have been on it for a while now, and now there is an effort to make Cognition open to the public, see an <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/01/elsevier-academic-publishing-petition/427059/">overview</a> in the Atlantic.</li>

